context: An <a4_0><b5_0><b6_0>incandescent light bulb<b6_0/><b5_0/><a4_0/>, incandescent lamp or incandescent light globe is an electric light with a <a1_0>wire filament<a1_0/> heated to a high temperature, by passing an <a0_0>electric current<a0_0/> through it, until it glows with visible light (incandescence). The hot filament is protected from oxidation with a glass or quartz bulb that is filled with inert gas or evacuated. In a halogen lamp, filament evaporation is prevented by a chemical process that redeposits metal vapor onto the filament, extending its life. The light bulb is supplied with electric current by <a2_0><b7_0>feed-through terminals or wires embedded in the glass<b7_0/><a2_0/>. Most bulbs are used in <a3_0><b8_0>a socket<b8_0/><a3_0/> which provides mechanical support and electrical connections.
